Class: IntroScene

h5c3. IntroScene

new IntroScene()

Handles the Publisher Splash screen, the Framework splash screen and will optionally handle the WebApp splash screen. See below how to enable automatic display of the WebApp splash.

setViewPort(x, y, width, height)

Sets the view port to the given top left postion (x, y) and dimensions (width and height) The view port represents the on-screen pixels dimensions of the game relative to the associated canvas. Use the view port dimensions to render different scenes at different positions on screen. e.g. a game layer would typically be 0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height whereas a mini map may just be in the top left corner of the screen (0, 0, 100, 100).
Parameters:
Name Type Description
x Number X position to render the scene within the canvas (in screen pixels)
y Number Y position to render the scene within the canvas (in screen pixels)
width Number The maximum width to render (in screen pixels)
height Number The maximum height to render (in screen pixels)
Inherited From:
  • h5c3.Scene#setViewPort
Source:
  • dist/h5c3.debug.cat.js, line 8978

setViewPort(x, y, width, height)

Sets the view port to the given top left postion (x, y) and dimensions (width and height) The view port represents the on-screen pixels dimensions of the game relative to the associated canvas. Use the view port dimensions to render different scenes at different positions on screen. e.g. a game layer would typically be 0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height whereas a mini map may just be in the top left corner of the screen (0, 0, 100, 100).
Parameters:
Name Type Description
x Number X position to render the scene within the canvas (in screen pixels)
y Number Y position to render the scene within the canvas (in screen pixels)
width Number The maximum width to render (in screen pixels)
height Number The maximum height to render (in screen pixels)

setViewPort(x, y, width, height)

Sets the view port to the given top left postion (x, y) and dimensions (width and height) The view port represents the on-screen pixels dimensions of the game relative to the associated canvas. Use the view port dimensions to render different scenes at different positions on screen. e.g. a game layer would typically be 0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height whereas a mini map may just be in the top left corner of the screen (0, 0, 100, 100).
Parameters:
Name Type Description
x Number X position to render the scene within the canvas (in screen pixels)
y Number Y position to render the scene within the canvas (in screen pixels)
width Number The maximum width to render (in screen pixels)
height Number The maximum height to render (in screen pixels)
